## Why Internal Load Matters for Small and Medium Clubs

In an ideal world, every club would have GPS, heart rate systems, and force plates. In reality, many small and medium clubs don‚Äôt have the budget, staff, or time.

This is where **internal load** is your best ally.

### Internal vs External Load (Simple View)

- **External load:**\
  What the athlete *did* (distance, high-speed running, accelerations, jumps, etc.).
- **Internal load:**\
  How the athlete‚Äôs body *responded* (RPE, heart rate, blood markers, etc.).

Even when two players cover the same distance at the same speed, their **internal training load** can be very different due to fitness, fatigue, stress, or injury history.

For small clubs:

- External load tech may be **too expensive** or hard to manage.
- Internal load via RPE/session-RPE is **cheap, universal, and quick**.
- It respects the athlete‚Äôs **subjective experience**, which research consistently shows is valuable for understanding fatigue and readiness.

**Benefits of focusing on internal load:**

- Works with **simple tools** (forms, apps, or platforms like [Fractall](https://fractall.fit/)).
- Easy to implement in **football, futsal, basketball, handball** and more.
- Gives a **whole-squad view** of how demanding your week really was.

**Coach Takeaway:**\
If you can‚Äôt measure everything, measure what matters most and is **realistic for your context**. Session-RPE gives you a robust, science-backed metric without needing hardware.

